  <h2>What Is Cold Laser Therapy?</h2>
  <p>
    Also called low-level laser therapy (LLLT) or photobiomodulation, cold laser therapy uses specific wavelengths of light to penetrate tissue and stimulate cellular repair. Unlike surgical lasers, cold lasers produce no heat and cause no tissue damage — making treatments comfortable and stress-free for most pets.
  </p>
  <p>
    Sessions typically last between five and thirty minutes depending on the treatment area and condition being addressed.
  </p>

  <h2>Benefits of Laser Therapy</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pain relief</strong> — stimulates the release of endorphins and reduces nerve sensitivity for measurable pain reduction</li>
    <li><strong>Reduced inflammation</strong> — decreases pro-inflammatory compounds and improves circulation in the treated area</li>
    <li><strong>Faster healing</strong> — promotes cell regeneration and accelerates tissue repair after injury or surgery</li>
    <li><strong>Non-invasive</strong> — no needles, no incisions, no sedation required for most patients</li>
    <li><strong>Drug-free option</strong> — beneficial for pets who cannot tolerate certain medications or for whom you want to minimize pharmaceutical use</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Conditions We Treat with Laser Therapy</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Arthritis and degenerative joint disease</li>
    <li>Hip dysplasia and elbow dysplasia</li>
    <li>Post-surgical incision healing</li>
    <li>Intervertebral disc disease (IVDD)</li>
    <li>Muscle strains, sprains, and soft tissue injuries</li>
    <li>Wounds, hot spots, and dermatological conditions</li>
    <li>Chronic pain in senior pets</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Expect</h2>
  <p>
    Most pets tolerate laser therapy well and many find it relaxing. A handheld device is moved gently over the target area. You may notice your pet becoming calm or even sleepy during treatment. Some pets show improvement after a single session; others benefit most from a series of treatments over several weeks.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our veterinary team will evaluate your pet and design a treatment plan appropriate for their specific condition and health history.
  </p>

